# SKILL.md Template

Use this template when drafting a SkillCraft-compatible Agent Skill. Replace bracketed fields with concrete content before publishing.

````markdown
---
name: [lowercase-hyphen-name]
description: [State what the skill does and when to use it. Include concrete trigger scenarios because this field is the primary discovery surface.]
---

# [Readable Skill Title]

## When To Use

Use this skill when [specific user situation].

Good fits:

- [Concrete trigger 1]
- [Concrete trigger 2]
- [Concrete trigger 3]

Do not use this skill for [nearby but unsupported request].

## Inputs

Ask for or infer these inputs:

- [Input 1]
- [Input 2]
- [Input 3]

If [critical input] is missing, ask for it before proceeding.

## Workflow

1. [Action-oriented step]
   - [Decision rule or detail]
   - [Quality-preserving instruction]

2. [Action-oriented step]
   - [Decision rule or detail]
   - [Quality-preserving instruction]

3. [Action-oriented step]
   - [Decision rule or detail]
   - [Quality-preserving instruction]

## Output Format

Return Markdown with this structure:

```markdown
## [Output Section]

- [Field]:
- [Field]:

## [Output Section]

<content>
```

## Quality Checks

- [Observable check]
- [Observable check]
- [Observable check]

## Failure Boundaries

- Do not [unsafe or unsupported behavior].
- Do not [source, privacy, or policy violation].
- Stop and ask for clarification if [condition].
````

## Authoring Notes

- Keep the skill body lean. Move detailed reference material into `references/` only when the skill truly needs it.
- Write workflow steps as actions an agent can execute.
- Make output formats checkable.
- Include examples in a separate `examples/` document when the example is long.
- Avoid "best prompt" language. Describe a repeatable skill workflow and how to validate it.
